[primary possible location of a csproj file]Show moreArchitected multi-project structure balancing per-submod organization with optional compilationArchitected multi-project structure balancing per-submod organization with optional compilationLooking at this, you're essentially building a multi-project mono-repo where Cake needs to selectively compile only the submods that have C# source. That's a very solvable pattern — here's how I'd fill in the [ ] spots and why.
The core decision: per-submod csproj, not a root csproj
Put the .csproj in the secondary location (inside each submod folder), not the root obj/ folder. Skip the root csproj entirely. Reasons:

Each submod is independently packageable (your bin/submodXPackaged output already treats them as separate units), so each should compile independently too.
Cake can then just glob for *.csproj under each submod folder to decide whether to build it — no manual "build list" to maintain.
A submod with no .csproj (like submodB in your tree) is automatically skipped, which matches your requirement that some submods won't produce a .dll.

Don't put a csproj in root obj/. obj/ is an MSBuild-generated intermediate folder (created automatically during restore/build) — it's not something you author into. If you want root-level shared config, use Directory.Build.props instead (see below). I'd drop the root obj/ from your planned structure unless something else needs it.
Revised structure
bin/
  submodAPackaged/ ...
  submodBPackaged/ ...
  submodCPackaged/ ...
submodA/
  assets/
  src/
  modinfo.json
  submodA.csproj        <-- secondary location, used here
submodB/
  assets/
  src/                  <-- empty or no .cs files
  modinfo.json          <-- no .csproj, nothing to compile
submodC/
  assets/
  src/
  modinfo.json
  submodC.csproj
CakeBuild/
  bin/
  CakeBuild.csproj
  obj/
  Program.cs
Directory.Build.props    <-- NEW: shared MSBuild settings, root level
build.cake                <-- your Cake script entry point (if not already CakeBuild/Program.cs)
Why Directory.Build.props instead of a root .csproj
MSBuild auto-imports Directory.Build.props into every project below it in the tree, without you referencing it manually. That gives you a clean place for things every submod should share:
xml<Project>
  <PropertyGroup>
    <TargetFramework>net7.0</TargetFramework>
    <LangVersion>latest</LangVersion>
    <Nullable>enable</Nullable>
    <OutputPath>bin\$(MSBuildProjectName)\</OutputPath>
  </PropertyGroup>
</Project>
Then each submod's .csproj stays minimal:
xml<Project Sdk="Microsoft.NET.Sdk">
  <ItemGroup>
    <!-- e.g. Reference to the modding API dll, if applicable -->
    <Reference Include="VintagestoryAPI">
      <HintPath>..\lib\VintagestoryAPI.dll</HintPath>
    </Reference>
  </ItemGroup>
</Project>
(Adjust that reference to whatever framework/API this is actually targeting — I'm inferring modding-framework conventions from modinfo.json + assets + dll packaging, so double check the actual target framework/API your game or platform expects.)
Cake script logic (pseudocode)
csharpvar submodDirs = GetDirectories("./submod*");

foreach(var dir in submodDirs)
{
    var csproj = GetFiles(dir.FullPath + "/*.csproj").FirstOrDefault();
    var packagedDir = "./bin/" + dir.GetDirectoryName() + "Packaged";

    if (csproj != null)
    {
        DotNetBuild(csproj.FullPath, new DotNetBuildSettings {
            OutputDirectory = packagedDir
        });
    }

    // Always copy assets + modinfo.json regardless of whether a dll exists
    CopyDirectory(dir + "/assets", packagedDir + "/assets");
    CopyFile(dir + "/modinfo.json", packagedDir + "/modinfo.json");
}
This naturally handles submodB having no .csproj — it just skips the build step and copies assets/modinfo only, matching the bin layout you already sketched.
One open question for you
Do submods need to reference each other (e.g. does submodC depend on types from submodA)? If so, you'll want ProjectReference entries between the .csproj files rather than relying purely on the folder convention — worth deciding now since it affects build order in the Cake script.one submod may depend on code contained inside of another submod, so that remain be a possibility.Use the Directory.Build.props instead of creating duplicate information in the individual csproj files when possible.Refine the cake script to do the following
get all directories which contain a modinfo.json file inside of them instead of "./submod*"
the packaged dir name should remain the same as the directory name (submodA/[assets/,modinfo.json,src/] = bin/submodA/[assets/,modinfo.json,submodA.dll])Reconsidered build dependencies and refined directory discovery logicReconsidered build dependencies and refined directory discovery logicGood call on both counts. Here's the refinement.
Handling cross-submod dependencies
Since a submod's code can depend on another submod's code, use ProjectReference between the relevant .csproj files:
xml<!-- submodC.csproj -->
<Project Sdk="Microsoft.NET.Sdk">
  <ItemGroup>
    <ProjectReference Include="..\submodA\submodA.csproj" />
  </ItemGroup>
</Project>
The good news: you don't need to manually order the Cake build. dotnet build resolves ProjectReference dependencies transitively — if you tell it to build submodC.csproj, it will build submodA.csproj first automatically. So your Cake loop can iterate in any order and MSBuild handles the graph correctly. (Just make sure there are no circular references between submods — MSBuild will fail loudly if there are.)
Directory.Build.props — centralizing shared config
Move anything common (framework, langversion, nullable, and now also common references like the modding API) up into the root props file so individual .csproj files only declare what's unique to them (their own ProjectReferences):
xml<!-- /Directory.Build.props -->
<Project>
  <PropertyGroup>
    <TargetFramework>net7.0</TargetFramework>
    <LangVersion>latest</LangVersion>
    <Nullable>enable</Nullable>
    <ImplicitUsings>enable</ImplicitUsings>
    <!-- Output goes to bin/<ProjectName>/ to match your packaged layout -->
    <BaseOutputPath>$(MSBuildThisFileDirectory)bin\$(MSBuildProjectName)\</BaseOutputPath>
    <AppendTargetFrameworkToOutputPath>false</AppendTargetFrameworkToOutputPath>
  </PropertyGroup>

  <ItemGroup>
    <Reference Include="VintagestoryAPI">
      <HintPath>$(MSBuildThisFileDirectory)lib\VintagestoryAPI.dll</HintPath>
    </Reference>
  </ItemGroup>
</Project>
Now a minimal submod csproj (e.g. submodB, if it later gets code) is just:
xml<Project Sdk="Microsoft.NET.Sdk" />
And submodC, which depends on submodA, only needs to state that one unique fact:
xml<Project Sdk="Microsoft.NET.Sdk">
  <ItemGroup>
    <ProjectReference Include="..\submodA\submodA.csproj" />
  </ItemGroup>
</Project>
Refined Cake script
csharp// Discover every directory containing a modinfo.json, anywhere under the root
var modDirs = GetFiles("./**/modinfo.json")
    .Select(f => f.GetDirectory())
    .ToList();

foreach (var dir in modDirs)
{
    var dirName = dir.GetDirectoryName();          // e.g. "submodA"
    var csproj = GetFiles(dir.FullPath + "/*.csproj").FirstOrDefault();
    var packagedDir = "./bin/" + dirName;           // name matches source dir, no suffix

    EnsureDirectoryExists(packagedDir);

    if (csproj != null)
    {
        DotNetBuild(csproj.FullPath, new DotNetBuildSettings {
            Configuration = "Release",
            OutputDirectory = packagedDir
            // ProjectReferences (e.g. submodA) are built automatically as part of this call
        });
    }

    // Always copy assets + modinfo.json, dll or not
    if (DirectoryExists(dir.FullPath + "/assets"))
        CopyDirectory(dir.FullPath + "/assets", packagedDir + "/assets");

    CopyFile(dir.FullPath + "/modinfo.json", packagedDir + "/modinfo.json");
}
Key changes from before:

Discovery: GetFiles("./**/modinfo.json") walks the whole tree recursively rather than assuming a submod* naming pattern — so it'll pick up submodA, submodB, submodC (and anything else with a modinfo.json) without you having to name them a particular way. This also means CakeBuild/ won't accidentally get swept in, since it has no modinfo.json.
Output naming: bin/submodA instead of bin/submodAPackaged — matches your spec exactly.

One thing worth flagging: DotNetBuild with OutputDirectory set to packagedDir will dump all build output there (dll, pdb, deps.json, any referenced-but-not-merged dependency dlls). If submodC references submodA, building submodC.csproj will likely also drop a copy of submodA.dll into bin/submodC/. If you don't want that duplication, you'd either post-build-copy just the primary dll, or set submodA's reference as <Private>false</Private> in the ProjectReference so it's treated as reference-only, not copied. Let me know if you want that tightened up.use the cake documentation to write the actual build script without pseudo code. The bin folder at the top is the bin folder to output to. The script location is to be located in CakeBuild/Program.cs
